<h2>
Introduction:</h2>
This lab provides experience defining functions.
<h2>
Lab Assignment:</h2>

<ol>
<ol>
<li>
Create a new directory, <i>lab7</i>, and move to it.</li>

<li>
Write a working program and, function <tt><u>round(fpnum,digits)</u></tt> which
it calls, which requests from the user a positive floating point number
(to round) and an integer in the interval
[0-6] specifying the number of decimal places to round to.
</li>

<ol>
    <li>
    <ul>
	<li>Base your equation on expressions from Exercise 21 of Section 4-12 of your C++ text.
	<li>Notice that the power of 10 used is equal to the number of digits to round to.
	<li>What function can you use to generate powers of 10?
    </ul>
</li>

<li>
Ensure that your program and functions have updated <u>comment </u>headers
describing your identifying information, the date, and the purpose of the
program or function.<br>
Each user defined function should document what each
parameter is and whether they are IN, OUT, or IN/OUT. <br>

<li>
Use a <b>function</b> to <u>prompt</u> the user with explicit instructions to
<u>input</u> the positive floating point decimal number to be rounded
<i>and</i> the number of digits to round to.<br>
The number of digits to round should be between zero and six inclusive <i>[0-6]</i>.
</li>

<li>
Use a <i>second</i> <b>function</b> to perform the rounding to the specified number
of decimal places.
</li>

<li>
<u>Output</u> the results using a <i>third</i> <b>function</b>.<br>
The output will display:
    <ul>
	<li>
	the original number,
	<li>
	the number of digits to round, and
	<li>
	the rounded value.
    </ul>
</li>

<li>
<b>Note</b>:
<ul>
<li>
Don't forget to place the <u>prototype declaration</u>
for each function above the function header of the main program.
<li>
Use <b>stubs</b> (See Program 4-13 on pg. 165) to design from the top down
and ensure that the functional structure is working at an intermediate stage.  When the stub form is working properly, replace each with the complete code and test.
</ul>
</li>

<li>
Compile and run.<br>
Ensure that the program is working correctly.<br>
Use <b>1.345678</b> as the input number.<br>
Test with rounding to 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 and 6 decimal places.
</li>


<li>
When correct, generate a printout of the source, and demonstrate, via
typescript, the running of the program for "checkout".</li>
</ol>

